            <h2>Globular Star Clusters</h2>
            <p style="font-size:.7em;">Each is a round collection of stars. Some have a greater central concentration (such as M2). Others seem to be evenly spread about (see M55).
Containing many thousands of stars. These stars orbit a common center. Some might contain a central black hole.
No known globular clusters display any star formation. All of their stars are older and lack heavy elements, suggesting they formed long ago.
Between 150-180 such clusters surround our galaxy in a “halo”. These were used by Harlow Shapley to make a determination of the dimensions of our galaxy and our location within it.
</p>
