					<section>
            <h2>Open Star Clusters</h2>
            <p style="font-size:.7em;">Visibly different that Globular Clusters, Open Clusters contain at most a few thousand stars formed in the same star-forming cloud of gas and dust. M45 still has some of this dust. Mostly young, hot stars, which are blue in color.
Loosely bound together, they will drift apart over time. In irregular galaxies, open clusters may be found throughout the galaxy, although their concentration is highest where the gas density is highest.
In our galaxy, open clusters are found in the spiral arms where gas densities are highest and most star formation occurs. Open clusters are not seen in elliptical galaxies where star formation ceased many millions of years ago.</p>
						<img data-src="/img/lapo/osc_m45.jpg" />
